@node abou "What the hell is this ?"
@toc "main"

This program was devised out of (yet more) frustration from other
software developers doing major changes to their software, thus
ruining the current installation.  In this case MAME.  The update
from MAME V0.29 to V0.30+ on the Amiga allowed the possibility to
use the roms (games) in their original Zip'ed form, or have them
compressed with LHA or LZX.  LZX gives better compression than Zip
so it would be wise to use that method.

But if like me, you had an old install of MAME you would have
hundreds of individual drawers inside the main MAME drawer.  Now,
instead of deleting all those game directories and their roms
(like someone I know did - hi Brad !) and redownloading them all
again  you could go to all the trouble of archiving them one by
one.  I thought of doing this and came to the conclusion of
'f*ck that'.

So I sat down and wrote MUpdater, which will automate the task
for you.


@endnode

@node inst "What, where, how and Why ?"
@toc "main"

Installation is very very simple.  Drag the icon (and thus the
program) to where ever you want to store it.  Thats it.  There
isn't an install script, what the hell for !?  Two files, well
four if you include the documentation and their icons...  Big
deal.


@endnode

@node reqs "Whats required ?"
@toc "main"

This is the big one right here.  This program, whilst not very
complex actually requires at a minimum Workbench 2.x and above.

There are no checks for Workbenck 1.3 and it will crash, so don't
try it.  Besides, is anyone but UAE users using WB 1.3 anymore ?

You will also need the following:


° Reqtools.library ¦  Used for all the requester and the Progress
                      Indicator.

° LHA, LZX, ZIP    ¦  V1.38+, V1.20+, V2.2+.  Please use the latest
                      versions available if possible.

° Delete           ¦  Used when the 'Delete Originals' option is
                      selected.

° A complete install of MAME. (@{i}MUpdater@{ui} will work if you
  only have a partial install, but a full latest release install
  is preferred.)


@endnode

@node disc "It isn't my fault"
@toc "main"

If this program doesn't work, then tough.  All I have to say is:

It worked on my machine.

@endnode

@node usag "So, what do I do ?"
@toc "main"

Using @{i}MUpdater@{ui} is very simple.  Follow these guidelines and you
can't go wrong.

Explanation of the GUI:

@{b} Start @{ub}

This button starts the whole archiving process off.  Before
pressing this though you must set both the @{b}MAME Directory@{ub}
and the @{b}ROMs Directory@{ub}.


@{b} About @{ub}

Gives some simple info on the program.  Not much here really.  :)


@{b} LZX, LHA, ZIP @{ub}

These three mutually exclusive radio buttons choose the archiving
method that @{i}MUpdater@{ui} uses to compress your MAME directory.

I would suggest using LZX as this gives the best compression method.
At the moment compression levels cannot be set and are set to their
default values.  This I feel is quite adequate but may change in
the future, although LZX does have problems using compression
mode 9 (highest compression, it requires the regsitered version,
and it's not very stable).


@{b} MAME Directory@{ub}

This will bring up a Reqtools path requester.  Here you must select
the directory that has your main MAME install.  This one directory
should contain all the other game directories in it.

Here is an example listing from my MAME directory:

2.work:temp/mame> dir

   ccboot (dir)
   ckonga (dir)
   commandj (dir)
   digdugat (dir)
   docastl2 (dir)
cheat.dat                       cheat.doc
mame060                         mame060.info
history.amiga                   readme.amiga


This is the directory that you should use as the @{b}MAME
Directory@{ub}.


@{b} ROMs Directory@{ub}

This is the directory that all the newly created archives will be
placed into.

This directory can be placed anywhere on your disk or in ram.  It
can even be in your original MAME dir.  Funky or what !?


@{b} Delete Originals@{ub}

If this box is selected then your original MAME directories and
the rom files inside them will be deleted.  This will save you
time by not having to do it yourself.


@{u} A Simple Tutorial @{uu}

Using the follonw method you should easily be able to archive
all your MAME roms into one directory and delete them afterwards,
saving you a lot of time and harddrive space.

If you have the Delete Originals box selected then your original
files and directories will be deleted for you, saving even more
time !


° Click on @{"MAME Directory" 0} and choose your @{b}main@{ub}
MAME directory.  eg.

2.work:temp/mame> dir

   ccboot (dir)
   ckonga (dir)
   commandj (dir)
   digdugat (dir)
   docastl2 (dir)
cheat.dat                       cheat.doc
mame060                         mame060.info
history.amiga                   readme.amiga


So, here you would choose "Work:temp/mame".  This can either be typed
into the selector in the path requester or be chosen via the gadgets.


° Click on @{"ROMs Directory" 0} and choose a directory to store
the MAME archived roms.  This can be any directory on your harddrive
or in ram.

EG. You could use any of the following:

work:temp/roms/

work:temp/

work:

games:temp/storage/roms/

work:temp/mame/roms/



°  Once you have set both directories choose the archiver you wish
to compress the game roms with by clicking on the relevant radio
button and then click @{"Start " 0} and wait.

°  The progress indicator will show you how far through the entire
process the program is.  You may, at anytime interrupt the archiving
process.  A requester confirming that you have interrupted the
archiving will open and the program will be reset to its initial state.


@endnode

@node bugs "I know, I know, it doesn't quite work right"
@toc "main"


Currently the program has the following bugs:


°  There are no checks for those clowns still using WB 1.3.

°  The program assumes you have enough ram left to do all the required
   task, and will possibly crash if there isn't.



@endnode

